    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  Accumulating evidence suggests that endogenous retroviruses (ERVs) play an important role in the host response to infection and the development of disease. By combining RNA- and ChIP-sequencing analyses with RT-qPCR, we show that SARS-CoV-2 infection induces the LTR69 subfamily of ERVs, both\n                  <jats:italic>in vitro</jats:italic>\n                  and\n                  <jats:italic>in vivo</jats:italic>\n                  . Using functional assays, we identified one SARS-CoV-2-activated LTR69 locus, termed Dup69, which exhibits enhancer activity and is responsive to the transcription factors IRF3 and p65/RelA. LTR69-Dup69 is located about 500 bp upstream of a long non-coding RNA gene (ENSG00000289418) and within the\n                  <jats:italic>PTPRN2</jats:italic>\n                  gene encoding a diabetes-associated autoantigen. Both ENSG00000289418 and\n                  <jats:italic>PTPRN2</jats:italic>\n                  showed a significant increase in expression upon SARS-CoV-2 infection. Thus, our study sheds light on the interplay of exogenous with endogenous viruses and helps to understand how ERVs regulate gene expression during infection.\n                </jats:p>",
